/*
DEEP COPY AND SHALLOW COPY

DEEP COPY ---> You copy the actual value (full independent clone)
👉 A deep copy creates a completely new object
👉 No shared references at any level

EXAMPLE
const obj1 = {
  name: "Agraj",
  address: {
    city: "Delhi"
  }
};
const obj2 = structuredClone(obj1); // deep copy
obj2.address.city = "Mumbai";
console.log(obj1.address.city); // ✅ Delhi (unchanged)

obj1.address ───> Delhi
obj2.address ───> Mumbai (separate copy)


Shallow Copy----->
👉 A shallow copy copies only the top-level properties
👉 Nested objects are still shared (same reference)

EXAMPLE
const obj1 = {
  name: "Agraj",
  address: {
    city: "Delhi"
  }
};
const obj2 = { ...obj1 }; // shallow copy

obj2.address.city = "Mumbai";
console.log(obj1.address.city); // ❗ Mumbai (changed!)

obj1.address  ─────┐
                   ├──> SAME MEMORY
obj2.address  ─────┘


*/

/*
Event Loop
❓ How does JS handle async things like setTimeout, API calls, promises?

👉 Answer: Event Loop


KEY RULE===>> 👉 Synchronous code > Microtasks > Macrotasks(PRIORITY ORDER)

LIST OF MACROTASK

setTimeout(): 

setInterval(): 

setImmediate()

I/O Tasks: Filesystem operations, network requests, etc.

UI Rendering: The browser’s internal process of drawing pixels on the screen.

Event Listeners: Clicks, scrolls, and keypress events.

Script execution: The initial loading of a <script> tag.

LIST OF MICROTASK

Promises: Specifically the .then(), .catch(), and .finally() callbacks.

Async/Await: Since await is syntactic sugar for Promises, the code after an await behaves like a microtask.

MutationObserver: Used to watch for changes in the DOM tree.

queueMicrotask(): A manual way to add a task to this queue.

##flow diagram how js handel task being single threaded

Call Stack
   ↓
Web APIs (Timer, Fetch, DOM)
   ↓
Queues:
   - Microtask Queue (Promises)
   - Macrotask Queue (setTimeout)
   ↓
Event Loop:
   - Run all microtasks
   - Run one macrotask
   - Repeat

*/

